These imagines or figures were usually ranged in the public apartment (atrium) of the house occupied by the repre- sentative of the family3 appropriate descriptive legends (tituli) were attached to each; they were exhibited on all great family or gentile festivals and solemnities; and the dignity of a family and of a gens was, to a certam degree, estimated by the number which it could dis- play· All persons who possessed one or more of these figures, Le. all who could number among their ancestors individuals who had held oue or more curule offices, were designated by the title of nobiles. All who had no figures of their ancestors and had not, in their own persons, attaiued to a curule office, were ranked together as ignobiles. Even after the admission of the Plebeians to a full participation in political power, the higher offices were, to a great extent, monopolisecl by a small number of families; these nobiles became gradually more and more exclusive, and looked ,vith very jealous eyes upon every one not belonging to their own class who sought to rise to eminence in the state.
